This longleaf pine was approximately 3 feet tall. Longleaf pine now are only found in 3 percent of their original range of 90 million acres. Conservation of the tree is important to the biodiversity of over 30 endangered and threatened species. For example the red-cockaded woodpeckers rely on longleaf pines for their habitat. 

RCWs are unique in their nesting, as they only nest in self-made cavities in live pine trees, as opposed to dead trees which most woodpeckers prefer.  Resin wells are also excavated by RCWs below their cavities to prevent predators from climbing cavity trees and robbing nests.  2006, FWC began a statewide RCW Safe Harbor Program through an agreement with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service under the Federal Endangered Species Act (ESA).  The goal of the program is to help conserve the RCW through partnerships with private landowners.

Since RCWs are protected under the ESA, landowners have a legal obligation to protect the birds and their habitat.  The program currently includes 15 private properties and approximately 65,000 acres. Safe Harbor Agreements make sense whenever landowners are interested in restoring or enhancing habitats that may benefit this endangered species but are concerned about incurring additional regulatory restrictions on the use of their land.  It effectively freezes a landowner's ESA responsibilities as long as the owner agrees to restore, enhance, or create habitat that benefits red-cockaded woodpeckers.  The Safe Harbor Program has many benefits to landowners, but the primary incentive is the certainty they gain regarding future land use. Property owners can maintain, restore or enhance red-cockaded woodpecker habitat, with the assurance that additional birds will not result in more land use restrictions. Description: The bark is thick, reddish-brown, and scaly. The leaves are dark green and needle-like, and occur in bundles of three. They often are twisted and 20–45 cm (7.9–17.7 in) in length. The cones, both female seed cones (ovulate strobili) and male pollen cones (staminate strobili), are initiated during the growing season before buds emerge. Pollen cones begin forming in their buds in July. Pollination occurs early the following spring, with the male cones 3–8 cm (1.2–3.1 in) long. The female (seed) cones mature in about 20 months from pollination; when mature, they are yellow-brown in color, 15–25 cm (5.9–9.8 in) long, and 5–7 cm (2.0–2.8 in) broad, opening to 12 cm (4.7 in), and have a small, but sharp, downward-pointing spine on the middle of each scale. The seeds are 7–9 mm (0.28–0.35 in) long, with a 25–40 mm (0.98–1.57 in) wing. 
Distribution: Natural range includes most of the Atlantic and Gulf Coastal Plains from southeastern Virginia to eastern Texas and south through the northern two-thirds of peninsular Florida. The species also grows in the Piedmont, Ridge and Valley, and Mountain Provinces of Alabama and northwest Georgia.
Habitat: warm, wet temperate climates characterized by hot summers and mild winters.
-Longleaf pine forests are rich in biodiversity. They are well-documented for their high levels of plant diversity, in groups including sedges, grasses, carnivorous plants, and orchids.

description:
The longleaf pine is a coniferous evergreen tree. As can be seen, by the picture, it has a very long and thin stump followed by clusters of needlelike leaves at the top.  The color of the bark is dark brown and the pine needles are dark green. The estimated height of the tree is around 60 feet tall. For reference, the white stick next to the plant is 3 feet long. The bark of the tree is very textured and individual bark pieces are well defined. In fact, one of the defining characteristics of this species is its very thick textured bark. The observation was made in a very sandy, sunny, and dry habitat. This is also the habitat for most longleaf pines because they can be intolerant to very shady areas. This is another defining characteristic of this species because some pines prefer shady areas. The reproductive structures, which are cones, are not present in this picture. This may be because longleaf pines only produce a large number of cones every 7 years in a period called the mast period.
Reference- https://www.fs.fed.us/database/feis/plants/tree/pinpal/all.html#:~:text=GENERAL%20BOTANICAL%20CHARACTERISTICS%3A,living%204%20to%205%20centuries.

description:
This organism appeared to be a younger version of many organisms around it. It was only about 4 meters tall, was narrow, and had multiple branches that ended in tuffs of long green needle leaves. The leaves themselves were about at least 30cm in length. The bark on the organism was brown and, in some spots, looked like overlapping scales and was about 14cm thick.
To support the idea that this organism was a longleaf pine, The National Wildlife Federation states that longleaf pines are a type of evergreen conifer that have long needle-like leaves that can grow up to 46cm long that are found as bundles of three. They also state that mature trees grow to 24 to 30 meters tall and are covered in thick scaly bark with a single trunk that is 0.9 meters in diameter. As they get older, they will rid themselves of their lower branches and grow nearly straight (para. 1).
The habitat this organism was found in was the forest that had lots of pine needles along the ground.
Geographically, The National Wildlife Federation claims that this organism is found in small patches from southeastern Virginia to Florida and the west in Louisiana and east Texas (para 2).
Reference: Longleaf Pine. National Wildlife Federation. https://www.nwf.org/Educational-Resources/Wildlife-Guide/Plants-and-Fungi/Longleaf-Pine.

Visual Description: This tree is about 45 feet high with bark that is quite thick and sticky. It is a very dark brown bark; that color may change when the bark is dry. The leaves are needle-like and have a dark green color, and they are all in a bundle. They have huge branches that extend from the tree; each of the branches has bundles of leaves. Their cones seemed to be ready to bud, but they are not all the way there. 

Defining Characteristics: This tree is a seed plant gymnosperm. The pines and the cones define the tree as a gymnosperm as it does not have any fruit or flowers. The long pines in large bundles are what distinguishes this from other pines. 

Habitat: They are native to the southeastern United States and can be found along the coastal plain from southern Virginia to Texas. It also reaches the northern and central parts of Florida.

description:
NUMBER: 20210815
SPECIES: Slash Pine, Pinus elliottii Engelmann, 1880[1]
SUBSPECIES: South Florida Slash Pine, Pinus elliottii densa Little and Dorman, 1952[1]
OTHER NAMES: Dade County Pine;[2] South Florida Slash Pine, Pinus elliottii var. densa Little and Dorman, 1952.  The name “slash” either comes from (1) its habitat[3] or (2) being slashed to collect resin.
DISTINCTIONS: Needles in bundles of 2 (occasionally 3), 8-15 cm long, the leaf buds green to light brown.  Gray-brown, flaky, with orange under-bark; fire scars may be present on the lower trunk.  Cones are usually <15 cm long and each scale is tipped with a short spine; present all year.
LOCATION: backyard SW of our villa 920 St Andrews Blvd, Naples, FL 34113
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 26.107037, -81.714917
DATE: 15 August
MORTALITIES: In the winter of 2020, 1 tree died (Figs. A,B,C).  We examined it and found evidence of Black Turpentine Beetles, Dendroctonus terebrans (Olivier, 1795) (BTB, Figs. B,C), and 1 beetle specimen (Figs. D-G).  In the summer of 2021, 2 more adjacent trees began to die showing browning needles.  They also showed signs of BTB.  We surveyed 15 trees in the immediate area and found 5 more with BTB signs (8/15 infested).  We reluctantly recommended to our facility that they remove these trees.  The facility brought in a Tree Expert, who agreed with our analysis.
INFESTATION: Oddly, BTB does not kill Pine Trees.  It only infests sick trees that are in the process of dying.  This is an indicator, not a disease.  Healthy trees are not infested.
SIZE: up to 30 m (100 ft) tall and 1.2 m (4 ft) in diameter[2]
DIAGNOSIS: The case of these mortalities was unclear since they were haphazardly intermixed with healthy trees.  First, we suspected the intense and protracted drought.  However, surviving trees did not match home irrigation systems.  We therefore assume twisting root damage from Hurricane Irma (2017).
DISTRIBUTION: Endemic to southern half of Florida peninsula and Florida Keys.
USES: Historically, an important economic timber for naval stores, turpentine, and resin.[2]
SIMILAR SPECIES: Longleaf Pine, Pinus palustris Miller, 1768, has cones >15 cm long, silver-white buds, and in south Florida restricted to Lee County.
OBSERVERS: Dr. Ernest H. Williams, Jr.,[4,5,7,8] and Dr. Lucy Bunkley-Williams[4,4,75,9]
AFILIATIONS, ADDRESSES: [4]Extraordinary Professors, Potchefstroom Campus, North-West University, South Africa; Adjunct Professors, Research Field Station, Florida Gulf Coast University, 5164 Bonita Beach Road, Bonita Springs, FL 34134; [5]Dept. Marine Sciences, University of Puerto Rico (retired); [6]Dept. Biology, UPR (retired); [7]920 St. Andrews Blvd, Naples, FL 34113-8943; [8]e-mail ermest.williams1@upr.edu; cell 239-227-3645, ORCID 0000-0003-0913-3013; [9]Cell 787-467-2179, e-mail lucy.williams1@upr.edu, ORCID 0000-0003-1390-911x.
REFERENCES:
<>Gilman, E. F., D. G. Watson, R. W. Klein, A. K. Koeser, D. R. Hilbert, and D. C. McLean. 2018. Pinus elliottii: Slash Pine. Environmental Horticulture Department, UF/IFAS Extension ENH-622, originally published 1993. https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/publication/ST463
<>Langdon, O. G. 1963. Range of South Florida Slash Pine. Journal of Forestry 61: 384-385 (reprint). https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/pubs/ja/1963/ja_1963_langdon_002.pdf
<>Williams, E. H., Jr.  and L. Bunkley-Williams. 2021. Mortality of South Florida Slash Pine, Pinus elliottii densa, in Naples, Florida. Research Quality Report, iNaturalist #91344606, 15 August (open access) [585]
ADDITIONAL FOOTNOTES:
[1]Identification was peer-reviewed, text edited and condensed.  The entire, original text is in our available reprints 585.
[2]Wood prized for beauty, durability, and extraordinary characteristics: dense, strong, and highly resistant to decay and insect damage.  Closely resembles heart wood of Longleaf Pine, but denser and with a figurative grain pattern.  Dade County Pine was used widely in the construction of many historic buildings throughout South Florida, which have withstood many hurricanes.  Unfortunately, overharvested and few fully grown 30+ year, 30 m (100 ft), 1.2 m (4 ft) trees remain. 
[3]Named for its habitat "slashes" or swampy ground overgrown with trees and bushes.

description:
Visual description: This Longleaf Pine was observed at approximately 4.5 feet tall in its bottlebrush stage of development. https://longleafalliance.org/what-is-longleaf/the-tree/life-stages/
Long, green needles spiked out from the trunk about 1.5 feet off the ground up through the top and were approximately 10-15 inches in length. The trunk is roughly 3-4 inches in diameter. At the very top, the needles were particularly dense in number, growing straight up, as opposed to falling towards the ground.

Defining Characteristics: 
This organism is a gymnosperm. The long needle-like leaves are indicative of a pine, specifically the Longleaf Pine, which has the longest needles of all the eastern pine species. 

Habitat: This Longleaf Pine was found in the Violet Curry Nature Preserve in Lutz, Florida. It was located right along the waterline of a wetland area of the reserve. These pines range within patches from Virginia, South to Florida, and west to East Texas. These pines can survive in a variety of habitats but prefer sandy, dry, acidic soil. Despite this pine being found in a wetland area, sandy dry soil surrounded the area with many other pines and vegetation.

description:
Visual Description: The branches with pine needles on them were very high from the base of the tree, the lowest branches were about 20 feet from the ground. Most of the pinecones from the tree had fallen to the ground. The needles were very thin, growing in groups and were about 8 inches long. The color of the trunk was brown and the pine needles were green on the tree and brown/orange on the ground.

Defining Characteristics: This was identified as a pine tree due to the uniqueness of pine tree needles. Furthermore, the pinecones around the tree were also seen growing from the stems of the tree above. Pinecones are both the male and female portions of the reproductive system, indicating that this was a seeded plant.

Habitat: These trees were located all throughout the nature preserve, from right on the water to deeper into the woods. These are the most common pine trees found in the South Florida area.

References: 9 typical types of pine trees in Florida. ProGardenTips. (2021, January 18). Retrieved October 15, 2021, from https://www.progardentips.com/pine-trees-in-florida/.

Visual Description: This young tree was approximately 8 feet tall. Long, skinny, needle-like leafs typically characterized by pine trees. No cones were present, although age of the tree should be considered. Trunk was straight and narrow. The bark was reddish-brown and rough to the touch.

Defining Characteristics: Needle-like leaves that arise from the stem in bundles. Different species of pines will have different numbers of leaves in a bundle. The bundles are arranged in spirals about a stem, called whorls. Most pines are evergreen and will have leaves year round. 

Habitat:  This tree was found in a forest like habitat in Violet Cury Nature Preserve in Lutz, FL. Pines are native and inhabit most of the northern hemisphere. They can survive in temperate and subtropical climates and can be found at altitudes as high as 13 000 feet. 

Reference: https://science.jrank.org/pages/5233/Pines-General-characteristics.html

Visual Description: Longleaf pine is an evergreen conifer with the most extended leaves of the eastern pine species, earning it its common name. The needlelike leaves, which occur in three-leaf bundles, can reach a length of 18 inches (46 cm). Mature trees can reach heights of 80 to 100 feet (24 to 30 meters). The solitary trunk may grow up to three feet (0.9 meters) in diameter and is coated in thick, scaly bark. The trees' lowest branches are pruned organically, and they grow almost perfectly straight. 

Defining Characteristics: The Longleaf Pine's trunk has scaly, coarse, light orange-brown bark and erect branches that form an open, round crown. The flexible, dark green needles reach up to 18" in length, while the huge, spiny cones reach up to 10" in length and can last up to two years on the tree. After germination, the pine continues in a tufted, grass-like stage for the first five to seven years, developing slowly as the root structure develops. It grows at a mild to rapid rate after the grass stage. During the winter, the inch-long clusters of new growth are silver white. The roots are susceptible to construction disruption.

Habitat:  The trees are now only found in tiny areas across the range. Longleaf pines may thrive in various environments, although they favor sandy, dry, acidic soils between sea level to 2,300 feet in elevation (700 meters). They are shade-intolerant and require direct sunshine to thrive. Longleaf pines dominate and occasionally form pure stands when recurrent fires sweep the forest.

References:

Visual Description: Very tall, but slender, reaching a height about 60-80 feet. Has very flaky, light grey bark. The leaves are needle shaped with a bright green color. Leaves are about 10 inches long. Tree branches are also very skinny. 

Defining Characteristics: Part of the gymnosperms, specifically the coniferophytes, as seen with the characteristic needle-like leaves. A seedless, vascular tree that utilizes cones for reproduction. The branches of the tree are more concentrated on the top of the tree.      

Habitat: Found outside my neighborhood in Wesley Chapel, surrounded by many other Longleaf Pines, trees, and shrubs. Native to Southeastern United States, it can be found all over the Southern part of the United States, from California to Maryland. Prefers to grow in hot environments, with direct or partial sunlight, in acidic soil.

I observed this specimen at Lettuce Lake Park in Tampa, Florida (Lat 28.073871, Long: -82.375376) on 10/20/2021 at 10:54 AM.  I believe this species of pine tree to be a Longleaf Pine (Pinus palustris) as opposed to one of the other pines that are found in Florida.  This is because of the high branches, the amount of needles on the brances, the presence of pinecones, and the texture of the bark.  This was a naturally occurring tree that was found off of one of the walking paths.

Pictured is a small longleaf pine: it is about 6 feet tall, with long needle-like leaf structures and a small trunk with red bark. The longleaf pine is native to the area it was found in, or the southeastern united states, specifically Violet Cury Nature Preserve in Tampa, Florida. Very clearly not a mature longleaf pine, this pine could reach up to 125 ft in height, with large cones and thick bark.

description:
This series of photographs from June 2012 shows an area in Jasper County, Mississippi with a relatively old example of longleaf pine (*Pinus palustris*).  The series also includes some of the signage from the area which provides context on the area’s conservation history.  

The first image, created by merging two separate photographs, shows an individual longleaf pine tree that was identified as Mississippi's "champion," i.e. largest known example of the species in the state. A human (standing approximately 5.8 inches tall) can be seen to the left side of the base of the tree, giving an indication of scale.  I did not measure the diameter of the tree, but I estimate it was approximately 2 to 2.5 meters diameter at breast height (DBH).  Understory trees included hickory (*Juglans*) and sweetgum (*Liquidambar styraciflua*).  A poison ivy vine (Toxicodendron radicans) grew around the trunk and reached high into the canopy. 

Other than the signage from the area, I cannot find any other mention or description of the area or initial data/measurements supporting the claim that this is/was the state’s largest example of longleaf pine.  That being said, the claim seems plausible based on my other experiences exploring the state. This was an unusually large longleaf pine tree.  

It has been almost 10 years since I visited this site and so, while I don’t know it’s current status, aerial images of the site do not seem to indicate any major disturbances in the canopy since my visit. The location provided for this observation is approximate within 50 meters, but should suffice for relocating and re-measuring the champion tree, should that task be undertaken in the future.  I am uncertain of the land ownership status and current site access, ie., if the signs are not still standing, acquiring permission before visiting might be recommended.

description:
A skippering trip with Don Fraser and Clint Gibson; we hoped to refind the Duke's Skipper that I found on 14 Oct (we were not successful). We were mostly west of South Road and walked south to the wetland (which Clint investigated), then we crossed South Road to check out the large areas of blooming Carphephorus (Coastalplain Chaffhead). We returned to our cars, rehydrated, and then left this area (heading for Eagle Nest Sink) at 1332. The weather at the start was sunny and 77 degrees, with a light breeze. By the time we left, it was sunny and 87 degrees ("feels like" 89),

Two days ago, the dial that sets the exposure on my camera quit working. It froze in a rather nice position, allowing most of today's photographs to have been taken in a satisfactory exposure setting. I did not use image-editing software to alter any of these photographs, but I will lighten up images that cannot be identified because they are too dark.

0655-1008 CST: Chipola River Water Management Area (Calhoun County; return trip from yesterday)

1016-1118 CST: Altha Park (Calhoun County)

1122-1153 CST: Mount Olive Cemetery Road (Calhoun County)

1245-1304 CST: lunch at the Blountstown Subway (Calhoun County)

1335-1343 CST: Willis Bridge Park (Calhoun County; 1 species!)

1400-1506 CST: Chipola River Boat Ramp (Calhoun County)

1615-1708 CST: Sam Atkins Park (Calhoun County; we got rained out)

1845 CST: we checked into the Apalachicola Bay Inn (Franklin County). We ate at a rather pricey restaurant in Apalachicola, where all food was served in Styrofoam containers and plasticware, which was all thrown into the trash when we were finished; weird. 

We barely saw the sun on any of the three days; most photographs were taken under gloomy skies, which meant that I often had to boost the light saturation to get a usable image, even if the image ended up looking washed-out.

Val and I have set a goal of attaining 50 or more bird species in each of Florida's 67 counties (Val has reached or exceeded this total in 57 counties, while I have reached or exceeded 50 species in 56 counties). Calhoun County was our primary target this trip; we each started the trip with 14 species. Owing to Val's much-better hearing than mine, Val ended this day with 51 species, while I ended up with 45.
